Dataset import¶

Source: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/352/online+retail

Abstract: This dataset captures essential details from online retail transactions, encompassing diverse aspects of the purchase process. This comprehensive dataset allows for the analysis of purchasing patterns, sales trends, and customer behavior across different countries. It provides a valuable resource for exploring various aspects of online retail operations, from product popularity to geographical sales distribution. The inclusion of detailed transaction information enables researchers and analysts to delve into the dynamics of the online retail business and derive insights that can inform strategic decisions.

In [ ]:
retail_schema = StructType([
  StructField('InvoiceNo', StringType()),
  StructField('StockCode', StringType()),
  StructField('Description', StringType()),
  StructField('Quantity', IntegerType()),
  StructField('InvoiceDate', StringType()),
  StructField('UnitPrice', FloatType()),
  StructField('CustomerID', StringType()),
  StructField('Country', StringType())
])
In [ ]:
file_location = "./online_retail.csv"
file_type = "csv"

infer_schema = "true"
first_row_is_header = "true"
delimiter = ","

# The applied options are for CSV files. For other file types, these will be ignored.
df = spark.read.format(file_type) \
  .option("inferSchema", infer_schema) \
  .option("header", first_row_is_header) \
  .option("sep", delimiter) \
  .schema(retail_schema) \
  .load(file_location)

df = df.na.fill("Missing_ID", subset="CustomerID")
df = df.withColumn("Invoice_Date", to_date(substring(df.InvoiceDate, 1,8),"dd-MM-yy"))
df.limit(10).show()

Distibution of Product Price¶

The histogram provides insights into the distribution of product prices. The majority of unit prices fall within the 0 to 50 USD range, indicative of a range of casual products. However, notable exceptions exist, with a subset of luxury products commanding higher prices, exceeding 100 USD and extending to 200 USD or more. This variation in price points underscores the diverse product offerings within the dataset, catering to both affordable and higher-end markets.

Understanding the distribution of prices allows us to discern distinct customer segments targeted by the store. The range of product prices, spanning from affordable to luxury items, suggests a strategic approach to catering to diverse customer preferences. This segmentation strategy enables the store to appeal to a broad spectrum of clientele, accommodating both budget-conscious consumers and those seeking higher-end, premium products.

Fast moving and Slow moving Inventory¶

Two bar charts have been generated to distinguish between fast-moving and slow-moving inventory. This categorization is determined by considering the shopping period and calculating the average number of orders for each product code. These charts offer valuable insights for inventory planning, allowing the management to strategically address both fast-moving and slow-moving inventory. The distinction enables proactive measures, ensuring optimal inventory levels and appropriate strategies for managing slower-moving products in the store's portfolio.

In [ ]:
df_moving = spark.sql("""
    Select 
        StockCode, 
        Count(Date) as No_Month,
        Avg(Ord) as No_Ord
    From 
    (
        Select
            StockCode,
            substring(cast(Invoice_Date as String), 1, 7) as Date,
            count(distinct InvoiceNo) as Ord
        From Retail_Data
        where Quantity > 0
        group by StockCode, substring(cast(Invoice_Date as String), 1, 7)    
    )
    Group by StockCode
    Order by 2 desc, 3 desc                         
"""
)

df_moving = df_moving.toPandas()
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.bar(df_moving["StockCode"].head(10), df_moving["No_Ord"].head(10), color = 'green')

Return time per client¶

We computed the average time between two consecutive purchases to determine the return time, enabling the segmentation of customers into distinct groups: loyal and churn clients. This analysis provides insights into customer behavior by identifying those who exhibit regular and frequent purchasing patterns (loyal clients) as opposed to those who demonstrate longer intervals between purchases (churn clients). Such segmentation aids in tailoring targeted strategies for customer retention and engagement.

In [ ]:
df_return = df.select("CustomerID", "Invoice_Date")
df_return = df_return.dropDuplicates(["CustomerID", "Invoice_Date"])

from pyspark.sql.window import Window

windowSpec = Window.partitionBy("CustomerID").orderBy(desc("Invoice_Date"))

df_return = df_return.withColumn("row_number", row_number().over(windowSpec))
df_return_last = df_return
df_return_last = df_return_last.withColumn("row_number", df_return_last.row_number + 1)
df_return_last = df_return_last.withColumnRenamed("Invoice_Date", "Invoice_Date_last")
df_return = df_return.join(df_return_last, ['CustomerID', 'row_number'])
df_return = df_return.withColumn("gap_time", df_return.Invoice_Date_last - df_return.Invoice_Date)
df_return = df_return.withColumn("gap_time", df_return.gap_time.cast('int'))

df_return = df_return.groupBy("CustomerID").agg(round(avg("gap_time"),2).alias("avg_gap_time"))
df_return = df_return.sort("avg_gap_time", ascending=[False])

df_return = df_return.toPandas()
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.barh(df_return["CustomerID"].head(10), df_return["avg_gap_time"].head(10), color = 'red')
plt.ylabel("Client Code")
plt.title("Churn Client") 
plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.barh(df_return["CustomerID"].tail(10), df_return["avg_gap_time"].tail(10), color = 'green')
plt.ylabel("Client Code")
plt.xlabel("Avg return time")  
plt.show()

Market Basket Analysis¶

Market Basket Analysis (MBA) is a well-known analytical tool in the retail grocery domain. Below are few goals that you can achieve with MBA

  • Identify frequently purchased items (sell more of such TOP products to increase consumption)
  • Upsell and cross-sell products across brands, categories, subcategories and so on. For e.g. if eggs and milk are bought together very frequently, promote only one of them and the other sells automatically

We create the support for each stock code as Spark Dataframe below:

In [ ]:
df_prod_freq = df.filter(df.Quantity > 0)
df_prod_freq = df_prod_freq.groupby("StockCode").agg(count("InvoiceNo").alias("count_invoice"))

df_prod_freq = df_prod_freq.crossJoin(
    df_prod_freq.groupby().agg(sum("count_invoice").alias("sum_of_count_invoice"))
)

df_prod_freq = df_prod_freq.withColumn("count_invoice/sum_of_count_invoice", df_prod_freq.count_invoice / df_prod_freq.sum_of_count_invoice)


df_prod_freq.sort("count_invoice/sum_of_count_invoice", ascending = [False]).show(10)

To identify for the association rules we may need to understand about some metrics related to Market Basket Analysis:

  • Support: $ frequency(A,B) / (total_transaction) $ We use the support to find ou top N popular products.
  • Confidence: $ frequency(A,B) / frequency(A) $ Provides the probability of purchasing B , given that A is already in that transaction.
  • Lift: $ Support(A,B) / Support(A) * Support(B) $ Provides the probability of buying A and B, given A and B are already in that transaction

We use FPGrowth algorithms in pysspark.ml.fpm library for implementation of Market Basket Analysis.

In [ ]:
from pyspark.ml.fpm import FPGrowth

fpGrowth = FPGrowth(itemsCol="Stock_Set", minSupport=0.02, minConfidence=0.2)
model = fpGrowth.fit(df_agg)

Utilizing the product list and its corresponding frequency, we were able to define the top N most popular products. This analysis provides a clear understanding of the products that consistently attract the highest levels of customer interest and engagement. Identifying and acknowledging these popular items is essential for strategic decision-making, including inventory management, marketing strategies, and ensuring customer satisfaction with high-demand products.

Employing association rules, we have gained insights into the confidence and lift, allowing us to understand the likelihood of customers purchasing certain products together. This analysis reveals patterns such as which product (Product A) is most commonly followed by another (Product B) in a customer's shopping journey. The confidence metric indicates the probability of the association, while lift quantifies how much more likely the two products are purchased together compared to random chance. This information proves valuable for enhancing cross-selling strategies and optimizing product recommendations based on customer purchasing behavior.

In [ ]:
import networkx as nx

G_rules = nx.from_pandas_edgelist(
    rules,
    source="antecedent",
    target="consequent",
    edge_attr="lift",
    create_using=nx.MultiDiGraph(),
    )

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
width = rules["lift"].values / 20
nx.draw_circular(
    G_rules,
    node_color="lightgreen",
    edge_color="red",
    width=width,
    with_labels=True,
    node_size=400,
)
plt.show()

To predict the likelihood of a customer choosing a specific product next in their shopping journey, we utilized the GraphFrame library to analyze the 'inDegrees.' This approach allows us to examine the incoming connections to each product node within the graph, providing insights into which products are frequently chosen in the sequence. By understanding the in-degree centrality, we can identify products that often precede or influence subsequent purchasing decisions, aiding in the refinement of product placement and recommendation strategies.

In [ ]:
from graphframes import *

rules_spark = model.associationRules.sort("confidence", ascending=[False]).limit(30)
vertices = rules_spark.select("antecedent").union(rules_spark.select("consequent")).distinct()
vertices = vertices.withColumnRenamed("antecedent", "name")
vertices = vertices.withColumn("id", vertices.name)
edges = rules_spark.select("antecedent", "consequent")
edges = edges.withColumnRenamed("antecedent", "src")
edges = edges.withColumnRenamed("consequent", "dst")

g = GraphFrame(vertices, edges)
g.inDegrees.sort("inDegree", ascending = [False]).show()

Time Series Forecasting¶

In order to delve deeper into time series forecasting, we integrated the Prophet library with PySpark to generate sales forecasts. Leveraging Spark SQL, we orchestrated the creation of a Pandas DataFrame specifically designed for time series analysis. This approach allows us to harness the forecasting capabilities of Prophet while benefiting from the distributed processing capabilities of PySpark, enabling accurate predictions and insights into future sales trends.

In [ ]:
ts = spark.sql(""" 
    Select

from prophet import Prophet
import logging

logging.getLogger('py4j').setLevel(logging.ERROR)

model = Prophet(
  interval_width=0.95,
  growth='linear',
  daily_seasonality=False,
  weekly_seasonality=True,
  yearly_seasonality=True,
  seasonality_mode='multiplicative'
  )
 
# fit the model to historical data
model.fit(ts_pd)

We calculate the accuracy of the model using MAE, MSE and RMSE

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
from math import sqrt
from datetime import date
 
# get historical actuals & predictions for comparison
actuals_pd = ts_pd[ ts_pd['ds'] < date(2018, 1, 1) ]['y']
predicted_pd = forecast_ts_pd[ forecast_ts_pd['ds'] < pd.to_datetime('2011-12-10') ]['yhat']
 
# calculate evaluation metrics
mae = mean_absolute_error(actuals_pd, predicted_pd)
mse = mean_squared_error(actuals_pd, predicted_pd)
rmse = sqrt(mse)
 
# print metrics to the screen
print( '\n'.join(['MAE: {0}', 'MSE: {1}', 'RMSE: {2}']).format(mae, mse, rmse) )
